            <p>Philadelphia January 17th&#44; 1887<lb/>
                Tebeth 21st 5647<lb/></p>
            <p>To the President and Board of Trustees of the Jewish Theological Seminary<lb/></p>
            <p>Gentlemen<lb/></p>
            <p>Among the applicants for the position<lb/> of Preceptor in the Preparatory Classes of our Institution&#44; the Rev.<lb/> Dr. B. Drachman who submitted to undergo an examination&#44; has my<lb/> approval.  I found that his knowledge of the Bible is extensive and<lb/> well grounded&#44; that he is conversant with the Mishnah&#44; and that he<lb/> understands the grammar and genius of the Hebrew language.  The secular<lb/> learning which the applicant has already attained&#44; his appearance and<lb/> bearing and specially the religious views&#44; which&#44; I have reason to<lb/> think&#44; he holds&#44; and which harmonize with those we wish to see inculcated&#44;<lb/> commend him to your consideration as fit for the office that he desires<lb/> to fill.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours very respectfully<lb/>
                S. MORAIS<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
